One of the most striking findings from experimental semantics and pragmatics is the pervasiveness of gradience in aggregated measures.1 While semanticists have long recognized the existence of gradience in some domains‚Äìe.g.¬†gradable adjectives‚Äìwe often assume categorical distinctions in other domains‚Äìe.g.¬†factivity. And even where traditional approaches assume categorical distinctions, experimental methods often reveal continuous variation. For the reasons laid out above, understanding this gradience is crucial for developing theories that connect formal semantics to behavioral data.

